 for bestpractices and # Project Detail Prompt

You are an AI development tool prompt author. Use this prompt to guide a development team (or AI code generator) to build the LifeOps Project Detail feature set described below. Meet all structural and runtime safety requirements exactly as specified in the “Mandatory Coding Standards — Runtime Safety.” Include concrete data models, API contracts, UI components, interactions, and acceptance criteria. Ensure every piece of code or pseudo-code guards against null/undefined values before calling array methods, uses data ?? [] when handling Supabase results, and initializes React state for arrays/objects with proper defaults.

---

## Project Detail

- TARGET PAGE: Project Detail
- Description: A single-project view that consolidates backlog, roadmap items, tickets, PRs, agent-run history, and action widgets. It integrates with the Project Management Automation layer (roadmaps, ticketing automation, PR summarization, release notes generation, CI/CD integrations via agents) and connects to supporting pages: Ticket Board (Kanban board with agent automation rules, bulk edits, sprint planning), CI & Integrations Page (repository links, CI/CD connectors, deployment targets, integration health with logs/test triggers), and Projects Dashboard (developer-centric hub with roadmaps, active tickets, PRs, releases, CI status, and agent-suggested actions).

- Core Goals:
  - Provide a coherent, responsive, and highly interactive single-project cockpit.
  - Reflect Roadmaps, Backlog, Tickets, PRs, and Agent History in a unified layout.
  - Enable agent-driven actions (triage, release notes, summarization) with explicit auditing and reversibility.
  - Offer action widgets and an Approvals/Cronjobs integration surface for scheduled workflows and governance.

- Connected Features:
  - Project Management Automation: Roadmaps, ticket automation, PR summarization, release notes generation, CI/CD integrations via agents.
  - Agent Run History: Audit trails, run artifacts, and traceable inter-agent messages.

---

## Overview

- The Project Detail page serves as the Command Center for a single LifeOps project. It aggregates:
  - Project header (name, owners, status, integrations)
  - Backlog section with quick-add and status indicators
  - Roadmap items (timeline, status, owners)
  - Tickets and PRs (summary, status, assignees)
  - Agent-run history (recent runs, outcomes, links to run artifacts)
  - Action widgets (start agent runs, generate release notes, run CI checks)
- The UI follows a dark, dense, developer-centric design system with a focus on clarity, auditability, and fast scanning.

---

## Page Description (Full Detail)

- What this page is:
  - A cohesive, multi-pane project cockpit for LifeOps, presenting backlog, roadmap, tickets, PRs, and agent-run history, with direct controls to trigger automation actions and browse historical run data.
- Goals:
  - Provide a single source of truth for a project’s current state and recent automation activity.
  - Enable fast triage, planning, and release preparation via integrated agent actions and templated workflows.
  - Maintain an auditable trail of agent decisions, prompts, inputs, outputs, and artifacts.
- Connected features:
  - Roadmaps (driven by Roadmap items tied to the project)
  - Ticketing automation (auto-generated tickets from backlog or roadmap needs)
  - PR summarization (summaries of PRs for release notes or stakeholder briefs)
  - Release notes generation (agent-generated notes from changes across tickets/PRs)
  - CI/CD integrations via agents (build/test/deploy status surfaced, with agent-triggered actions)
- UI Elements & Visual Guidance:
  - Project Header: 
    - Name, owner avatars/handles, status badge, integrations status (health indicators, last sync)
    - Action: Quick-Connect integrations, set project status
  - Backlog Panel:
    - List with search, filter, and quick-add input
    - Inline status chips (New, In Progress, Blocked, Done)
  - Roadmaps Panel:
    - Timeline-style or grouped cards with progress bars, owners, due dates
  - Tickets Panel:
    - Summary cards per ticket with status dot, priority badge, assignee avatars
  - PRs Panel:
    - List of PRs with summarize/expand actions, status, and checks summary
  - Agent History Panel:
    - Activity feed with recent agent runs, user actions, run IDs, and links to logs
  - Action Widgets:
    - Run Agent Triage, Generate Release Notes, Create Release, Trigger CI/CD, Schedule Cronjobs
  - Interactions:
    - Drag-and-drop for priorities, bulk actions (bulk edit), and sprint planning quick-access
- API Integrations:
  - No external APIs are required beyond internal LifeOps services; all data comes from the internal data layer (Postgres/Supabase-like) or internal agent orchestration services.

---

## Components to Build

- ProjectDetailPage
  - Layout: header, left navigation (collapsed/expanded), main content grid with resizable panels
  - Data adapters: fetch project by id, fetch related backlog, roadmaps, tickets, PRs, agent history
  - State management: useState with array defaults; useEffect data fetch; proper null checks
- ProjectHeader
  - Displays project name, owners, status, integrations status
  - Actions: connect integrations, quick status toggle
- BacklogPanel
  - List with search, filters, add-new task input, bulk select
  - Actions: add backlog item, bulk update status
- RoadmapPanel
  - Roadmap items with progress, owner, due date; edit-in-place
  - Drag-and-drop reordering within lanes or priority
- TicketsPanel
  - Card list of tickets with status, priority, assignee; supports bulk actions
- PRsPanel
  - Card list of PRs with summarize action, status, checks
- AgentHistoryPanel
  - Activity feed including run IDs, agents, results, and log links
- ActionsWidgetBar
  - Quick action buttons: Run Agent Triage, Generate Release Notes, Trigger CI/CD, Schedule Cronjob
- CronjobsDashboardLink
  - Link to Cronjobs dashboard with next run time and last run outcome
- QuickAddModal
  - For backlog and ticket quick-add with validation
- BulkEditModal
  - Apply bulk updates to selected items
- DataVizTinyCharts
  - Lightweight sparkline views for project metrics (CI status, ticket counts)
- DataAdapters/Services
  - ProjectService, BacklogService, RoadmapService, TicketService, PRService, AgentService, HistoryService
- UI Primitives
  - Button, Input, Select, Badge, Card, Avatar, Toggle, Chips, Tabs, Drawer/Panel

Note: All components must guard against null/undefined values before using array methods. Follow the runtime safety rules throughout.

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend

- Architecture:
  - React (with TypeScript) components, hooks-based state, context for project scope
  - Component composition: header > left nav > content grid with resizable panels
- UI Components & Interactions:
  - Panels render data from services; handle loading, empty states, and error states gracefully
  - All arrays initialized with safe defaults: e.g., const [backlog, setBacklog] = useState<BacklogItem[]>([])
  - Use data ?? [] when mapping API results
  - Use Array.isArray checks where needed
  - Bulk actions: multi-select with bulk edit modal
  - Drag-and-drop for backlog/tickets roadmaps (optional MVP with keyboard-accessible reordering)
  - Quick-add forms with inline validation and optimistic UI updates
  - Agent actions: trigger agent via API, display run status, show logs link
  - Tabs: Card sections with consistent spacing and titles
- Accessibility:
  - Keyboard navigable controls, ARIA attributes for dynamic panels
- State & Data Loading:
  - Use suspense/fetch policy patterns or loading skeletons
  - Debounce search inputs; pagination or infinite scroll for long lists
- API Contracts:
  - Consistent shapes with strict type definitions; validate shapes defensively

### Backend

- APIs to support frontend data needs (if not existing):
  - GET /api/projects/:projectId
  - GET /api/projects/:projectId/backlog
  - GET /api/projects/:projectId/roadmaps
  - GET /api/projects/:projectId/tickets
  - GET /api/projects/:projectId/prs
  - GET /api/projects/:projectId/history
  - POST /api/projects/:projectId/backlog (create)
  - POST /api/projects/:projectId/tickets (create)
  - POST /api/agents/run (start agent run)
  - POST /api/cronjobs/trigger (manually run cronjob)
- Data Models (schemas):
  - Project: id, name, owners[], status, integrations[]
  - BacklogItem: id, title, description, status, priority, assigneeId, createdAt
  - RoadmapItem: id, title, status, ownerId, dueDate, progress
  - Ticket: id, title, status, priority, assigneeId, backlogItemId, createdAt
  - PR: id, title, state, checksSummary, authorId, linkedTicketIds[]
  - AgentRun: id, agentName, type, status, startedAt, endedAt, logsUrl, artifactsUrl
  - CronJob: id, name, enabled, schedule, timezone, target, inputPayload, permissions, safetyRails, retryPolicy, outputs
- Validation:
  - Ensure all inputs are validated server-side; reject invalid payloads with descriptive errors
- Security:
  - Authenticate requests; enforce authorization per project; audit trails for agent actions
- Data Safety:
  - Use transactions for multi-record updates; ensure consistency between related panels

### Integration

- How components connect:
  - ProjectDetailPage consumes ProjectService data
  - Each Panel subscribes to relevant services (BacklogService, RoadmapService, TicketService, PRService, HistoryService)
  - Agent actions trigger AgentService endpoints; run artifacts linked to AgentRun records
  - Cronjobs integration surfaces (CronjobsDashboardLink) point to a central Cronjobs module
- Dataflow:
  - On page load, fetch project and related collections in parallel; coerce results with data ?? [] and Array.isArray checks
  - On user actions (add/edit), optimistically update UI, persist via API, then reconcile on response
  - All actions produce run artifacts and logs; expose links in AgentHistoryPanel

---

## User Experience Flow

1. User navigates to Project Detail for a specific project.
2. Page loads: header shows project name and status; panels render backlog, roadmaps, tickets, PRs, and history; action widgets are visible.
3. User uses BacklogPanel to search, filter, or quick-add a backlog item; UI validates input; on submit, item appears in UI and persists.
4. User opens RoadmapPanel to view items; drags to reorder or updates progress; changes persist and reflect across UI.
5. User reviews TicketsPanel and PRsPanel; can bulk select tickets to bulk-edit or assign; click “Summarize PR” to trigger PR summarization by agent.
6. User clicks an Action Widget (e.g., Run Agent Triage) to start an agent run; a lightweight status toast appears; AgentHistoryPanel updates with the new run.
7. AgentRun results render in AgentHistoryPanel with a link to logs/artifacts; user can click and view details.
8. User navigates to Cronjobs via the Actions area to schedule or trigger a run; if approvals are required, an Approvals queue entry is created; user approves or adjusts constraints.
9. If needed, user switches to the connected pages (Ticket Board, CI & Integrations Page, Projects Dashboard) for deeper work, with consistent navigation breadcrumbs.

---

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models (TypeScript interfaces or schemas):
  - Project
    - id: string
    - name: string
    - owners: string[]  // user IDs or handles
    - status: 'active' | 'paused' | 'archived'
    - integrations: string[]
  - BacklogItem
    - id: string
    - title: string
    - description?: string
    - status: 'New' | 'In Progress' | 'Blocked' | 'Done'
    - priority: 'Low' | 'Medium' | 'High'
    - assigneeId?: string
    - createdAt: string
  - RoadmapItem
    - id: string
    - title: string
    - status: 'Planned' | 'In Progress' | 'Completed'
    - ownerId?: string
    - dueDate?: string
    - progress: number  // 0-100
  - Ticket
    - id: string
    - title: string
    - status: 'Open' | 'In Review' | 'Closed'
    - priority: 'Low' | 'Medium' | 'High'
    - assigneeId?: string
    - backlogItemId?: string
    - createdAt: string
  - PR
    - id: string
    - title: string
    - state: 'OPEN' | 'MERGED' | 'CLOSED'
    - checksSummary?: string
    - authorId?: string
    - linkedTicketIds?: string[]
  - AgentRun
    - id: string
    - agentName: string
    - type: 'triage' | 'summarizePR' | 'generateReleaseNotes' | 'ciTrigger'
    - status: 'pending' | 'running' | 'succeeded' | 'failed'
    - startedAt: string
    - endedAt?: string
    - logsUrl?: string
    - artifactsUrl?: string
  - CronJob
    - id: string
    - name: string
    - enabled: boolean
    - schedule: string  // cron or UI-based
    - timezone: string
    - target: 'agent' | 'workflowTemplate'
    - inputPayload: any
    - permissions: 'suggest-only' | 'approval-required' | 'conditional-auto' | 'bounded-autopilot'
    - constraints: { maxActions?: number; spendLimit?: number; allowedTools?: string[] }
    - safetyRails: { confirmationsRequired: boolean; requiredUserRoles?: string[] }
    - retryPolicy: { maxRetries: number; backoffMs: number; deadLetter?: boolean }
    - outputs: { runHistoryId?: string; logs?: string[]; artifacts?: string[] }

- API Endpoints (RESTful guidance; implement in your tech stack):
  - GET /api/projects/{projectId}
  - GET /api/projects/{projectId}/backlog
  - GET /api/projects/{projectId}/roadmaps
  - GET /api/projects/{projectId}/tickets
  - GET /api/projects/{projectId}/prs
  - GET /api/projects/{projectId}/history
  - POST /api/projects/{projectId}/backlog
  - POST /api/projects/{projectId}/tickets
  - POST /api/agents/run
  - POST /api/cronjobs/trigger
  - GET /api/cronjobs?projectId={projectId}
  - PUT /api/projects/{projectId}/status
- Security:
  - JWT-based auth; role-based access control per project
  - Audit trail for all data mutations and agent runs
- Validation:
  - Server-side validation for all input payloads
  - Use defaults and type guards on responses
- Validation Rules:
  - All arrays should be treated as possibly null; guard before mapping
  - Always coerce data to expected types; fallback to safe defaults

- Validation Examples Guard Rules (runtime safety):
  - const backlog = Array.isArray(response?.data?.backlog) ? response.data.backlog : []
  - const items = (data ?? []) // Supabase-safe pattern
  - const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}
  - items.map(...) guarded by (Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [])

---

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] The Project Detail page renders with header, backlog, roadmaps, tickets, PRs, agent history, and action widgets, each backed by safe data-loading flows (no crashes if data is missing).
- [ ] All array operations guard against null/undefined: e.g., (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
- [ ] State initialization: all arrays use useState<T[]>([]) defaults; object states initialized safely.
- [ ] Actions (Run Agent, Generate Release Notes, Schedule Cronjobs) create AgentRun/CronJob records and reflect immediately in AgentHistoryPanel.
- [ ] Bulk edit and quick-add work without throwing on empty data; UI shows appropriate empty states.
- [ ] Data fetches are resilient: if a dataset is missing, the UI renders without crashing and shows empty-state indicators.
- [ ] Security: protected routes require authentication; unauthorized users cannot mutate project data; audit logs are created for agent runs and cronjob actions.
- [ ] UI consistency: components adhere to the provided visual style, typography, spacing, and color tokens.

